THIS is the day, fellow-citizens, which we celebrate. Let us remember it, with grateful hearts, to that Being, who said;
"Let there be light, and there was light."
Let us cherish the invigorating flame, which then burned in the bosom of our fathers and patriots, and hand it glowing to posterity. This is the day, which calls forth the sublime feelings of independence, and the congenial flow of American souls. We do not celebrate the romance of departed heroes, but the atchievements of our fathers. We do not celebrate the feasts of heathen Gods, but the anniversary of reason. We do not commemorate the building of thrones, or the coronation of kings; but, we commemorate the nativity of a nation, that memorable day, on which three million people were born to freedom! Let us remember, we are no longer subjects of ghastly tyranny; but the citizens of an unalianable commonwealth!
